Handwritten Digit Recognition
A complete machine learning project that classifies handwritten digits (0–9) from 8×8 pixel images using the UCI Optical Recognition of Handwritten Digits dataset.
What it does

Preprocessed 64 intensity features and engineered 23 additional spatial features (row/column sums, symmetry scores, centre of mass, etc.)
Implemented and compared three algorithms: Naïve Bayes, Support Vector Machines (RBF kernel), and Decision Trees
Used nested cross-validation (5 outer / 3 inner folds) with hyperparameter tuning and learning curve analysis

Results
SVM: 98.88% accuracy (best performer)
Naïve Bayes: 93.45%
Decision Trees: 89.93%

End-to-end ML pipeline with thoughtful feature engineering
Rigorous evaluation using nested cross-validation
Clear analysis of bias-variance trade-offs between models
Clean, reproducible Python code and detailed technical report

Technologies & Skills: Python, scikit-learn, Pandas, NumPy, Matplotlib, Feature Engineering, Model Evaluation, Cross-Validation
